## Walk-Through: `rt_shared_mem` E2E Test

This is the canonical hybrid-sim demo: it exercises **both** register transfer (via the state file) and memory transfer (via shared mmap) across all three simulators. Each phase mutates memory that the next phase observes.

### The test program (`hybrid_vsim/hybrid/test/rt_shared_mem.S`)

```asm
_start:
    // Phase A (runs in QEMU 1): fill 4 KB at 0x80010000 with 0xA5 bytes.
    li      t0, 0x80010000
    li      t3, 0xA5A5A5A5A5A5A5A5
    li      t1, 512
1:  sd      t3, 0(t0)
    addi    t0, t0, 8
    addi    t1, t1, -1
    bnez    t1, 1b

    csrwi   0x7C0, 0           // QEMU drains regs+PC -> state file, exits

    // Phase B (runs in vsim): verify the 0xA5 pattern is still there,
    // then XOR the page in place with 0x5A. After this loop every byte
    // is 0xA5 ^ 0x5A = 0xFF.
    li      t0, 0x80010000
    li      t3, 0xA5A5A5A5A5A5A5A5
    li      t4, 0x5A5A5A5A5A5A5A5A
    li      t1, 512
verify_a:
    ld      t2, 0(t0)
    bne     t2, t3, fail_b      // exit 50 if QEMU's writes did not survive
    addi    t0, t0, 8
    addi    t1, t1, -1
    bnez    t1, verify_a
    li      t0, 0x80010000
    li      t1, 512
xor_loop:
    ld      t2, 0(t0)
    xor     t2, t2, t4
    sd      t2, 0(t0)
    addi    t0, t0, 8
    addi    t1, t1, -1
    bnez    t1, xor_loop

    csrwi   0x7C0, 1            // vsim drains regs+PC -> state file, exits 200

phase_c:                        // (runs in QEMU 2): verify all 4 KB is 0xFF.
    li      t0, 0x80010000
    li      t5, -1
    li      t1, 512
verify_c:
    ld      t2, 0(t0)
    bne     t2, t5, fail_c      // exit 51 if vsim's writes did not survive
    addi    t0, t0, 8
    addi    t1, t1, -1
    bnez    t1, verify_c
    li      a2, 0
    SEMIHOST_EXIT a2            // PASS: exit 0
```

Three phases, with **two kinds of state** crossing each handoff boundary:

| Boundary | Register state (via state file) | Memory state (via shared mmap) |
|---|---|---|
| QEMU 1 -> vsim | PC must point at the instruction after `csrwi 0x7C0, 0`. All 32 GPRs are copied through the packed struct. | The 4 KB of `0xA5` bytes Phase A wrote is already on disk in `/dev/shm/vsim-rt-shared.*`. vsim sees it instantly via mmap. |
| vsim -> QEMU 2 | PC must point at `phase_c`. GPRs copied back through a second state file. | The page is now `0xFF` because vsim XOR'd it. QEMU 2's mmap of the same file sees it byte-for-byte. |

If `bne t2, t3, fail_b` ever fires, QEMU's memory writes did not survive into vsim. If `bne t2, t5, fail_c` fires, vsim's writes did not survive into QEMU 2. The test only exits 0 when **both** transfer paths work end to end.

### How register state moves: the state file

```
QEMU 1                                          vsim
  hybrid_handoff.so            state_qemu.bin           qemu_resume.hpp
  --------------------         ------------------        --------------------
  on csrwi 0x7C0, 0   --->     struct hybrid_state_v1    halt CPU via JTAG DM
  read x1..x31 via     write   { magic = 'AHYB',         for each reg: write
  qemu_plugin_         atomic  version = 1,                via DM Abstract Cmd
  read_register()      with    pc = <next insn after     set DPC = state.pc
  read PC, CSRs        O_TMPFILE  csrwi>,                issue 'dret' -> resume
  qemu_plugin_                  gpr[32] = {...},         at the right PC
  request_exit()                csr = {...}, ... }
```

The same packed struct (`include/hybrid/state_abi.h`, `struct hybrid_state_v1`) is the wire format on **both** sides. vsim drains symmetrically when it hits `csrwi 0x7C0, 1`, and the spawned QEMU 2 picks up the regs through its `gdbstub` `G` packet.

### How memory state moves: shared mmap

```
host shell           QEMU 1                  vsim                    QEMU 2
  truncate -s 128M
  /dev/shm/foo
       |
       +-- mmap'd at 0x80000000 in all three guest address spaces ----+
       |              |                         |                    |
       v              v                         v                    v
   one 128 MB       sd 0xA5...               ld / xor / sd          ld 0xFF...
   backing file     at GPA 0x80010000        at GPA 0x80010000      at GPA 0x80010000
                    -> file off 0x10000      -> same file off       -> same file off
```

Both guests are launched with the same backing file:
- QEMU 1: `-object memory-backend-file,share=on,mem-path=/dev/shm/foo -machine virt,memory-backend=mem`
- vsim: `--shared-mem-path /dev/shm/foo --shared-mem-size 128M`
- QEMU 2: spawned by vsim with the same `-object memory-backend-file,share=on,...` args.

A guest physical address `0x80010000` maps to file offset `0x10000` in every process. Loads and stores in any simulator hit the same OS page cache - no copying, no serialization, no synchronization needed beyond the handoff fence (each simulator has fully exited before the next starts).

### The driver (`hybrid_vsim/tests/hybrid/rt_shared_mem.sh`)

```mermaid
sequenceDiagram
    participant SH as rt_shared_mem.sh
    participant FS as /dev/shm/foo<br/>(128 MB mmap)
    participant Q1 as QEMU 1 + plugin
    participant VS as vsim
    participant Q2 as QEMU 2 (spawned by vsim)

    SH->>FS: truncate -s 128M (allocate empty backing file)
    SH->>Q1: launch with -object memory-backend-file,share=on,mem-path=foo<br/>+ -plugin hybrid_handoff.so,outfile=state_qemu.bin

    Note over Q1,FS: Phase A: writes 4 KB of 0xA5 at GPA 0x80010000
    Q1->>FS: mmap stores -> file offset 0x10000

    Q1->>Q1: hits csrwi 0x7C0, 0
    Q1->>SH: writes state_qemu.bin (regs + PC), exits

    SH->>VS: launch with --resume-from-qemu state_qemu.bin<br/>--shared-mem-path foo --qemu-binary qemu...
    VS->>VS: JTAG DM restores 32 GPRs and PC from state_qemu.bin
    VS->>FS: ld at 0x80010000 -> reads 0xA5 (QEMU's writes survived!)
    Note over VS,FS: Phase B: XOR loop -> page becomes 0xFF
    VS->>FS: sd at 0x80010000 -> file now contains 0xFF

    VS->>VS: hits csrwi 0x7C0, 1, drains regs+PC to state_vsim.bin
    VS->>Q2: fork+exec qemu -gdb tcp:... -S -semihosting<br/>-object memory-backend-file,share=on,mem-path=foo
    VS->>Q2: gdb 'G' packet with regs from state_vsim.bin, then 'c'
    Q2->>FS: ld at 0x80010000 -> reads 0xFF (vsim's writes survived!)
    Note over Q2: Phase C verify loop passes
    Q2->>VS: SEMIHOST_EXIT 0
    VS->>SH: process exits with code 0
    SH->>SH: assert exit code == 0 -> PASS
```

### What each step proves

| Step | What it tests |
|---|---|
| Phase A writes 0xA5 to mmap | QEMU's RAM backend is the shared file (not a private anonymous mapping). |
| QEMU 1 produces `state_qemu.bin` | The TCG plugin recognizes `csrwi 0x7C0, 0` and drains all 32 GPRs + PC + CSRs through the plugin API. |
| Phase B `verify_a` loop passes | **Memory written in QEMU survives into vsim.** Shared mmap works as advertised. |
| vsim runs the XOR loop | Resumed register state was correct - in particular `t0`, `t1`, `t3`, `t4` are reinitialized by Phase B but the **PC** must have been restored to point at Phase B's first instruction. |
| Phase C `verify_c` loop passes | **Memory written in vsim survives into QEMU 2.** Both transfer paths work. |
| Final exit code 0 | Full round-trip succeeded. Exit 50 means QEMU->vsim memory broke; exit 51 means vsim->QEMU memory broke. |

If any link breaks, the distinct exit codes tell you exactly which transfer path failed.

## Where to Look Next

- `include/hybrid/state_abi.h` - the wire contract; both QEMU plugin and vsim include this exact header.
- `qemu_plugin/hybrid_handoff.c` - the QEMU side. Look at `resolve_handles` and the entry-trigger callback.
- `hybrid_vsim/src/hybrid/` - the vsim side: `qemu_resume.hpp`, `state_drain.hpp`, `csr_trigger.hpp`, `qemu_handback.hpp`.
- `hybrid_vsim/hybrid_plan.md` - the original design document, with full rationale for every decision.
- `run_e2e.sh` - run all e2e tests locally without going through CMake/CTest.

## Mental Model in One Sentence

> Two simulators agree on a memory map and a register struct, take turns running the same program, and use a magic CSR write as the baton-pass.
